{"data":{"actions":[{"callId":"chatcmpl-tool-a3348a601bf9f25a","input":{"filename":"etl-data-quality-prioritized-action-report.md","title":"ETL Data Quality Monitor Prioritized Action Report","markdown":"# ETL Data Quality Monitor – Prioritized Action Report\n\n**Scope**: Review of the current ETL data‑quality queue for the *Data* team, based on the latest dossier and the top three risk‑scored records (limit = 20).\n\n---\n\n## 1. Findings & Classification\n\n| ID | Title | Status | Impact | Risk Score | Primary Classification |\n|----|-------|--------|--------|------------|------------------------|\n| **37‑A** | ETL data quality monitor priority case | urgent | 53,729 | **10** (high) | **Schema** – possible drift / structural change detected. |\n| **37‑C** | ETL data quality monitor blocked follow‑up | blocked | 25,807 | **6** (medium) | **Completeness** – missing downstream metrics; requires cross‑team coordination. |\n| **37‑B** | ETL data quality monitor routine queue item | in_review | 13,181 | **2** (low) | **Freshness** – latency spikes observed but within SLA. |\n\n### Evidence\n- The *analyze_records* tool returned the three highest‑scoring items with their risk/opportunity scores.\n- No live data queries were performed; the conclusions rely on the provided risk model.\n\n### Assumptions\n- The risk model correctly weights schema drift as the most critical threat to downstream analytics.\n- Blocked status for 37‑C indicates a dependency that cannot be resolved by the monitor alone.\n- Impact values are comparable across items (higher = greater business effect).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Prioritized Actions (under 500 words)\n\n### **Urgent – Item 37‑A (Schema Drift)**\n1. **Run immediate schema validation** on the affected source tables (use the monitor’s `validate_schema` routine).  \n2. **Generate a drift report** and alert the data‑engineering owner.  \n3. **Deploy a hot‑fix**: either revert recent schema changes or update downstream mappings.\n4. **Document the change** in the version‑controlled schema registry.\n\n### **High – Item 37‑C (Blocked – Completeness)**\n1. **Identify the blocking dependency** (e.g., downstream service, data‑catalog refresh).  \n2. **Facilitate a cross‑functional sync** (Data Engineering + Platform Ops).  \n3. **Create a temporary data‑quality shim** that flags missing fields rather than halting the pipeline.  \n4. **Track resolution** in the incident tracker; once cleared, re‑run the completeness audit.\n\n### **Medium – Item 37‑B (Routine – Freshness)**\n1. **Review latency metrics** for the last 24 h; confirm they remain within the agreed SLA.  \n2. **Adjust alert thresholds** if current values show a trend toward SLA breach.  \n3. **Add a periodic freshness check** to the monitor’s nightly health‑check suite.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Next Steps & Monitoring\n- **Weekly risk recalibration**: run `analyze_records` every Monday to surface new high‑risk items.\n- **Dashboard update**: surface the three classifications on the team’s “ETL Health” board for quick triage.\n- **Post‑mortem**: after resolving 37‑A, conduct a root‑cause analysis to prevent similar schema drift.\n\n---\n\n*Prepared by the ETL Data Quality Monitor (agent 37‑etl-data-quality-monitor).*\n"},"kind":"tool-call","toolName":"write_report"}],"sequence":0,"stepIndex":3,"turnId":"turn_0"},"type":"actions.requested","meta":{"at":"2026-06-18T15:23:13.778Z"}}
